text:
West 165th Street, west from Amsterdam Avenue, showing at the right the area to be cleared for steet widening. This will leave a triangular plaza facing the R. C. Church of St. Rose of Lima (left). Beyond the solitary tenement that is to be demolished, appears a glimpse of the Wm. Fox Audubon Theatre.

April 30, 1924

Standard Photographic Service
Gift of Borough President of Manhattan

West 165th Street, east from Audubon to Amsterdam Avenue, showing the 4 story tenement (with undertaking sign) that is to be removed in the regulating and grading contract. To the right appears the R. C. Church of St. Rose of Lima. In the foreground are the St. Nicholas Avenue cartracks.

April 30, 1924

Standard Photographic Service
Gift of Borough President of Manhattan

(1)
2121 and 2123 Amsterdam Avenue, east side, between 165th and 166th Streets. Note that No. 2123 is set back some distance from the street, with its front yard converted into a parking space.

These two houses were the first to be erected in this block, and were built between 1879 and 1885. At that time this was Tenth Avenue; the name Amsterdam was not used till nearly 1890.

October 12, 1934.

P. L. Sperr, Photographer.

(2)
A closer view of 2123 Amsterdam Avenue, and parking grounds in front.

October 12, 1934.

P. L. Sperr, Photographer.
